- All rows with a ClassificationURI value must also have a ClassificationLabel value. - Addressed

- GeoAreaLabel must exactly match the offiicalname of the GeoAreaURI, including any punctuation. The following do not match:
* http://statistics.data.gov.uk/id/statistical-geography/E05005144
* http://statistics.data.gov.uk/id/statistical-geography/E05005140
* http://statistics.data.gov.uk/id/statistical-geography/E05005145 - Addressed

- Status value must be from the list provided in the documentation - 'Refuse' and 'Approve' are not on the list. - Addressed

- DecisionType value must also be from the provided list. 'COMM', 'DEL' and 'NOCODE' are not in the list. - Addressed

- PublisherLabel must be 'Tunbridge Wells' to match the PublisherURI label. - Query about this as your website has tunbridge_wells ????

- GeoX and GeoY must be filled in if possible, or details provided in the form's Applicant Notes to say why the data couldn't be provided (e.g. licence restrictions). - Addressed

17/07/2014I'm just checking the required schema for this data against the schema of the data we already have published to our open data website (http://www.opendatanottingham.org.uk/dataset.aspx?id=75). I can see that our data has been altered and used in the example file available from your website. While it's good to know that our data is being discovered, I have some reservations about the schema used. My concern is that while it seems to ensure the data is machine readable, and has become less human-readable. In particular in the 'EntertainmentTypeLabel' column the contents of several other fields have been concatenated and now become far less easy for a visual scan through to find premises that might meet a certain criteria.
